'revision','',0),(194,3,'2017-01-17 19:03:27','2017-01-18 00:03:27','','anatomy-of-a-nnu-union-card','','inherit','closed','closed','','anatomy-of-a-nnu-union-card','','','2017-01-17 19:03:27','2017-01-18 00:03:27','',119,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Anatomy-of-a-NNU-Union-Card.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(195,3,'2017-01-17 19:03:49','2017-01-18 00:03:49','','nnu-union-card','','inherit','closed','closed','','nnu-union-card','','','2017-01-17 19:03:49','2017-01-18 00:03:49','',119,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/NNU-Union-Card.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(196,3,'2017-01-17 19:04:12','2017-01-18 00:04:12','','anatomy-of-nnu-card','','inherit','closed','closed','','anatomy-of-nnu-card','','','2017-01-17 19:04:12','2017-01-18 00:04:12','',119,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Anatomy-of-NNU-Card.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(197,3,'2017-01-17 19:06:29','2017-01-18 00:06:29','','15-questions-to-ask-union-organizers','','inherit','closed','closed','','15-questions-to-ask-union-organizers-2','','','2017-01-17 19:06:29','2017-01-18 00:06:29','',137,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/15-questions-to-ask-union-organizers.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(198,3,'2017-01-17 19:08:10','2017-01-18 00:08:10','','benefits-today-vs-with-union','','inherit','closed','closed','','benefits-today-vs-with-union','','','2017-01-17 19:08:10','2017-01-18 00:08:10','',149,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Benefits-today-vs-with-union.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(199,3,'2017-01-17 19:09:23','2017-01-18 00:09:23','','how-well-do-you-know-the-union','','inherit','closed','closed','','how-well-do-you-know-the-union','','','2017-01-17 19:09:23','2017-01-18 00:09:23','',147,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/How-well-do-you-know-the-union.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(200,3,'2017-01-17 19:12:29','2017-01-18 00:12:29','','nnu-lm2','','inherit','closed','closed','','nnu-lm2','','','2017-01-17 19:12:29','2017-01-18 00:12:29','',184,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/NNU-LM2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(201,3,'2017-01-17 19:12:31','2017-01-18 00:12:31','','how--spends-members-dues','','inherit','closed','closed','','how-nnu-spends-members-dues','','','2017-01-18 06:42:14','2017-01-18 11:42:14','',184,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/How-NNU-Spends-Members-Dues.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(202,3,'2017-01-17 19:12:51','2017-01-18 00:12:51','','nnu-financials','','inherit','closed','closed','','nnu-financials','','','2017-01-17 19:12:51','2017-01-18 00:12:51','',184,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/NNU-Financials.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(203,2,'2017-01-18 03:57:38','2017-01-18 08:57:38','<h2>What You Should Know About Signing a Union Card or Petition</h2>\nIf you’re thinking about signing an UFCW card or petition, be sure you’re informed about unions and how joining one can impact you and your family so that you can make a good decision based on facts.\n\nBayCare leadership is committed to providing fact-based information about unions, the law and your legal rights. We would prefer to keep our direct working relationship with employees so we may continue to work together to provide safe, excellent, patient-centered care.\n\nYou can obtain information about the UFCW – and even go to UFCW meetings – without signing a union authorization card, petition or sign-in sheet.\n\nUnion organizers use different ways to get employees to sign authorization cards or petitions, such as:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Visiting your home and asking you to sign a card or petition</li>\n 	<li>Inviting you to meetings at local restaurants or colleague’s homes</li>\n 	<li>Approaching you while at work</li>\n 	<li>Sending letters or communications to you by text, e-mail, Facebook or other online resources</li>\n 	<li>Sending materials to your home with union authorization cards attached</li>\n</ul>\nOrganizers also may say things or even make promises they can’t keep in order to coerce you to sign an authorization card. UFCW and pro-union employees may tell you:\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “You should sign the card.  Everyone has signed but you.”</em></strong>\n\nFACT:     If “everyone” else had signed, the organizer wouldn’t need your signature. He or she would already have enough signatures to petition the National Labor Relations Board for an election. No one should be pressured into signing an authorization card or petition.  You have the legal right to sign or not sign a card or petition, based on what you think is best for yourself and your family, not based on what other employees have done.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “The union will strengthen our benefits.”</em></strong>\n\nFACT:     Unions make numerous promises; but they can’t guarantee any of them.  Unions offer a process – like collective bargaining – but they cannot guarantee results.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “Sign the card to show support for your colleagues. Since Florida is a right-to-work state so you won’t need to pay union dues.”</em></strong>\n\nFACT:     There are other ways you can support your colleagues.  Your colleagues shouldn’t expect you to attend a union meeting or sign a union authorization card to demonstrate your friendship, show loyalty to your unit or support fellow nurses.  Unionization can impact you and your family in many ways – and you may not agree with the decisions that UFCW or union delegates makes if the union were to win the right to represent you and your colleagues.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “Forming a union will give us a voice to advocate for our patients.”</em></strong>\n\nFACT:     Many BayCare employees already have a voice through shared decision-making groups. Unions generally oppose hospital efforts to directly involve employees in decisions because they give employees a real voice and make the union irrelevant.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “The union gives employees legal rights to protect ourselves and our patients.”</em></strong>\n\nFACT:     Employees have legal rights to advocate for themselves and their patients – without a union. BayCare also has policies and procedures through which any employee concerned about a work situation can report it to his/her manager or escalate the matter if he/she is dissatisfied with the manager’s response.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>MYTH:    “Try the union for a while. If you don’t like it, we’ll leave.”</strong>\n\nFACT:     Ending a relationship with a union is not as easy as organizers may say. Once\nthe union is voted in to represent you, it’s in place for at least one year even if no contract has been signed. If a contract is ratified and signed, you could have union representation for up to three more years. To change your mind about a union, you\nand your co-workers would need to file a petition, called a decertification petition, with the NLRB at the end of the contract.  You and your co-workers would be responsible for all legal costs related to the decertification effort – and the\norganization cannot help you.','Know Your Rights','','inherit','closed','closed','','111-autosave-v1','','','2017-01-18 03:57:38','2017-01-18 08:57:38','',111,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/111-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(204,2,'2017-01-17 22:54:40','2017-01-18 03:54:40','','protect-privacy-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','protect-privacy-icon','','','2017-01-17 22:54:40','2017-01-18 03:54:40','',140,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/protect-privacy-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(205,2,'2017-01-17 22:59:12','2017-01-18 03:59:12','','protect-privacy-icon1','','inherit','closed','closed','','protect-privacy-icon1','','','2017-01-17 22:59:12','2017-01-18 03:59:12','',140,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-conte