ns have to file with the U.S. Department of Labor annually.\n\nMembers pay a union for representation but in 2015-2016, UFCW Local 1625 sent more to UFCW’s corporate headquarters in Washington than to represent its members in Florida.\n\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/big-business-ufcw-spreadsheet.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-224\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/big-business-ufcw-spreadsheet.png\" alt=\"big-business-ufcw-spreadsheet\" width=\"887\" height=\"333\" /></a>\n\nUFCW spent:\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>$1,107,262</strong> on Representational Activities to represent its members – including negotiating contracts and organizing new members…. That’s less than $158 per member even though members may pay as much as $486 per year in UFCW dues.</li>\n 	<li>$525,757 on General Overhead, Union Administration and Benefits – salaries and benefits for union leaders and union employees</li>\n 	<li>$47,450 on Political Activities and Lobbying—which is not detailed in their LM-2… what is that money paying for?</li>\n</ul>','Big Business: How UFCW Spends Members’ Dues','','inherit','closed','closed','','113-autosave-v1','','','2017-01-18 03:53:28','2017-01-18 08:53:28','',113,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/113-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(224,2,'2017-01-18 03:49:39','2017-01-18 08:49:39','','big-business-ufcw-spreadsheet','','inherit','closed','closed','','big-business-ufcw-spreadsheet','','','2017-01-18 03:49:39','2017-01-18 08:49:39','',113,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/big-business-ufcw-spreadsheet.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(225,2,'2017-01-18 03:52:45','2017-01-18 08:52:45','','ufcw-financials','','inherit','closed','closed','','ufcw-financials','','','2017-01-18 03:52:45','2017-01-18 08:52:45','',113,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/UFCW-Financials.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(230,2,'2017-01-18 04:04:32','2017-01-18 09:04:32','<strong>A:</strong> A union authorization card/petition is a legal document that potentially can give a union the sole and exclusive right to speak and act on behalf of the employees in all matters regarding wages, benefits, working conditions and other terms of your employment at BayCare.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','What is a union authorization card/petition?','','publish','closed','closed','','what-is-a-union-authorization-cardpetition-3','','','2017-01-18 04:04:32','2017-01-18 09:04:32','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=230',0,'post','',0),(231,2,'2017-01-18 04:05:19','2017-01-18 09:05:19','<strong>A:</strong> Signing a card does not guarantee that you will get better wages or benefits or that issues and concerns will be resolved.  If the union becomes your exclusive representative, the only right it gives the union is to represent employees and negotiate a contract with BayCare.\r\n\r\n','Does signing a union card guarantee me better wages and working conditions?','','publish','closed','closed','','does-signing-a-union-card-guarantee-me-better-wages-and-working-conditions-3','','','2017-01-18 04:05:19','2017-01-18 09:05:19','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=231',0,'post','',0),(232,2,'2017-01-18 04:06:16','2017-01-18 09:06:16','<strong>A:</strong> Union organizers and employees who support them can be extremely persistent and aggressive.  We want you to have the facts about your legal rights.  Federal law provides employees with:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>The right to sign or not sign a union card</li>\r\n 	<li>The right to campaign for or against the union</li>\r\n 	<li>The right not to be bothered by union supporters while you are working or in patient care areas</li>\r\n 	<li>The right to talk or not talk to a union representative if you are contacted at home</li>\r\n 	<li>The right to tell union organizers you are not interested</li>\r\n 	<li>The right to say “no.”</li>\r\n</ul>','What are my rights if I don’t want to sign a union authorization card/petition?','','publish','closed','closed','','what-are-my-rights-if-i-dont-want-to-sign-a-union-authorization-cardpetition-3','','','2017-01-18 04:06:16','2017-01-18 09:06:16','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=232',0,'post','',0),(233,2,'2017-01-18 04:06:54','2017-01-18 09:06:54','<strong>A:</strong> The union can do several things with a signed authorization card/petition.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>If the union gets 30 percent of employees in an appropriate bargaining unit (employee group) to sign cards, it could go to the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) and file a petition for an election in which employees vote to determine whether or not they want to be unionized.</li>\r\n 	<li>If the union collects signatures from more than 50 percent of the employees in an appropriate bargaining unit, the union could request that we recognize the union as employees’ representative without holding a secret ballot election.</li>\r\n 	<li>The union may use this card to send you mail, to call you at home, text you or to visit you at home.</li>\r\n</ol>','Why is my signature so important to the union, and what does the union do with signed authorization cards/petitions?','','publish','closed','closed','','why-is-my-signature-so-important-to-the-union-and-what-does-the-union-do-with-signed-authorization-cardspetitions-3','','','2017-01-18 04:06:54','2017-01-18 09:06:54','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=233',0,'post','',0),(234,2,'2017-01-18 04:37:11','2017-01-18 09:37:11','','anatomy-of-an-ufcw-union-card','','inherit','closed','closed','','anatomy-of-an-ufcw-union-card','','','2017-01-18 04:37:11','2017-01-18 09:37:11','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Anatomy-of-an-UFCW-Union-Card.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(235,2,'2017-01-18 04:43:44','2017-01-18 09:43:44','','ufcw-eauth-cards-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','ufcw-eauth-cards-icon','','','2017-01-18 04:43:44','2017-01-18 09:43:44','',116,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/ufcw-eauth-cards-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(236,2,'2017-01-18 04:46:14','2017-01-18 09:46:14','','ufcw-financials-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','ufcw-financials-icon','','','2017-01-18 04:46:14','2017-01-18 09:46:14','',113,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/ufcw-financials-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(237,2,'2017-01-18 04:49:32','2017-01-18 09:49:32','','know-your-righs-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','know-your-righs-icon','','','2017-01-18 04:49:32','2017-01-18 09:49:32','',111,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/know-your-righs-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(238,2,'2017-01-18 05:21:03','2017-01-18 10:21:03','','position-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','position-icon','','','2017-01-18 05:21:03','2017-01-18 10:21:03','',64,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/position-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(239,2,'2017-01-18 05:42:57','2017-01-18 10:42:57','<h2>What You Should Know About Signing a Union Card or Petition</h2>\r\nIf you’re thinking about signing an NNU card or petition, be sure you’re informed about unions and how joining one can impact you and your family so that you can make a good decision based on facts.\r\n\r\nBayCare leadership is committed to providing fact-based information about unions, the law and your legal rights. We would prefer to keep our direct working relationship with employees so we may continue to work together to provide safe, excellent, patient-centered care.\r\n\r\nYou can obtain information about the NNU – and even go to NNU meetings – without signing a union authorization card, petition or sign-in sheet.\r\n\r\nUnion organizers use different ways to get employees to sign authorization cards or petitions, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Visiting your home and asking you to sign a card or petition</li>\r\n 	<li>Inviting you to meetings at local restaurants or colleague’s homes</li>\r\n 	<li>Approaching you while at work</li>\r\n 	<li>Sending letters or communications to you by text, e-mail, Facebook or other online resources</li>\r\n 	<li>Sending materials to your home with union authorization cards attached</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOrganizers also may say things or even make promises they can’t keep in order to coerce you to sign an authorization card. NNU and pro-union nurses may tell you:\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “You should sign the card.  Everyone has signed but you.”</em></strong>\r\n\r\nFACT:     If “everyone” else had signed, the organizer wouldn’t need your signature. He or she would already have enough signatures to petition the National Labor Relations Board for an election. No one should be pressured into signing an authorization card or petition.  You have the legal right to sign or not sign a card or petition, based on what you think is best for yourself and your family, not based on what other employees have done.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “The union will strengthen our benefits.”</em></strong>\r\n\r\nFACT:     Unions make numerous promises; but they can’t guarantee any of them.  Unions offer a process – like collective bargaining – but they cannot guarantee results.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “Sign the card to show support for your colleagues. Since Florida is a right-to-work state so you won’t need to pay union dues.”</em></strong>\r\n\r\nFACT:     There are other ways you can support your colleagues.  Your colleagues shouldn’t expect you to attend a union meeting or sign a union authorization card to demonstrate your friendship, show loyalty to your unit or support fellow nurses.  Unionization can impact you and your family in many ways – and you may not agree with the decisions that NNU or union delegates makes if the union were to win the right to represent you and your colleagues.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “Forming a union will give us a voice to advocate for our patients and nursing practice.”</em></strong>\r\n\r\nFACT:     Many BayCare nurses already have a voice through shared decision-making groups. Unions generally oppose hospital efforts to directly involve nurses in decisions because they give nurses a real voice and make the union irrelevant.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “The union gives RNs legal rights to protect ourselves and our patients.”</em></strong>\r\n\r\nFACT:     Nurses have legal rights to advocate for themselves and their patients – without a union.  BayCare also has policies and procedures through which any employee concerned about a work situation can report it to his/her manager or escalate the matter if he/she is dissatisfied with the manager’s response.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<strong><em>MYTH:    “Try the union for a while. If you don’t like it, we’ll leave.”</em></strong>\r\n\r\nFACT:     Ending a relationship with a union is not as easy as organizers may say. Once the union is voted in to represent you, it’s in place for at least one year even if no contract has been signed. If a contract is ratified and signed, you could have union representation for up to three more years. To change your mind about a union, you and your co-workers would need to file a petition, called a decertification petition, with the NLRB at the end of the contract.  You and your co-workers would be responsible for all legal costs related to the decertification effort – and the organization cannot help you.','Know Your Rights','','publish','closed','closed','','know-your-rights','','','2017-01-18 05:42:57','2017-01-18 10:42:57','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=239',0,'post','',0),(240,2,'2017-01-18 05:41:26','2017-01-18 10:41:26','','nnu-know-your-rights','','inherit','closed','closed','','nnu-know-your-rights','','','2017-01-18 05:41:26','2017-01-18 10:41:26','',239,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/NNU-Know-Your-Rights.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(241,2,'2017-01-18 06:06:44','2017-01-18 11:06:44','<h2><span style=\"color: #415a8a;\">The National Labor Relations Board has written about the Risks of Collective Bargaining:</span></h2>\r\n<strong>Are team members guaranteed the same benefits in a union contract that they had prior to collective bargaining?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>No</strong>. Your wages, benefits, work hours and employment terms may change because of bargaining. You could end up with less than you have now, more than you have now or keep the same as you have. It is not possible to know what will result from collective bargaining. In fact, the NLRB has said that:<strong>\r\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-242\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png\" alt=\"rocb1\" width=\"792\" height=\"141\" /></a>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Does an employer have to agree to union demands?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>No</strong>. A union can only get what management is able and willing to give.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-243\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png\" alt=\"rocb2\" width=\"783\" height=\"118\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Could NNU trade away in bargaining things you enjoy now to get things it wants – like the automatic deduction of dues from your paycheck?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Yes</strong>. Bargaining means give and take. At the table, some benefits may be traded for language that the union may want in a contract like dues “check off” – the automatic deduction of dues from your paycheck.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-244\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png\" alt=\"rocb3\" width=\"777\" height=\"116\" /></a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>In bargaining, everything is negotiable. There is no guarantee you will get more or will not end up with less!</strong><strong>\r\n</strong>','Risks of Collective Bargaining','','publish','closed','closed','','risks-of-collective-bargaining-2','','','2017-01-18 06:09:38','2017-01-18 11:09:38','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=241',0,'post','',0),(242,2,'2017-01-18 06:02:11','2017-01-18 11:02:11','','rocb1','','inherit','closed','closed','','rocb1','','','2017-01-18 06:02:11','2017-01-18 11:02:11','',241,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(243,2,'2017-01-18 06:03:08','2017-01-18 11:03:08','','rocb2','','inherit','closed','closed','','rocb2','','','2017-01-18 06:03:08','2017-01-18 11:03:08','',241,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(244,2,'2017-01-18 06:03:32','2017-01-18 11:03:32','','rocb3','','inherit','closed','closed','','rocb3','','','2017-01-18 06:03:32','2017-01-18 11:03:32','',241,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(245,2,'2017-01-18 06:06:33','2017-01-18 11:06:33','','rocb-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','rocb-icon','','','2017-01-18 06:06:33','2017-01-18 11:06:33','',241,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(246,2,'2017-01-18 06:07:25','2017-01-18 11:07:25','','nnu-risks-of-collective-bargaining','','inherit','closed','closed','','nnu-risks-of-collective-bargaining','','','2017-01-18 06:07:25','2017-01-18 11:07:25','',241,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/NNU-Risks-of-Collective-Bargaining.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(247,2,'2017-01-18 06:16:07','2017-01-18 11:16:07','<h2><span style=\"color: #4f81bd;\">The National Labor Relations Board has written about the Risks of Collective Bargaining:</span></h2>\r\n<strong>Are team members guaranteed the same benefits in a union contract that they had prior to collective bargaining?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>No. </strong>Your wages, benefits, work hours and employment terms may change because of bargaining. You could end up with less than you have now, more than you have now or keep the same as you have. It is not possible to know what will result from collective bargaining. In fact, the NLRB has said that:\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-242\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png\" alt=\"rocb1\" width=\"792\" height=\"141\" /></a>\r\n\r\n\r\n</strong><strong>Does an employer have to agree to union demands?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>No</strong>. A union can only get what management is able and willing to give.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-243\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png\" alt=\"rocb2\" width=\"783\" height=\"118\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Could UFCW trade away in bargaining things you enjoy now to get things it wants – like the automatic deduction of dues from your paycheck?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Yes. </strong>Bargaining means give and take. At the table, some benefits may be traded for language that the union may want in a contract like dues “check off” – the automatic deduction of dues from your paycheck.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-244\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png\" alt=\"rocb3\" width=\"777\" height=\"116\" /></a>\r\n</strong><strong>In bargaining, everything is negotiable. There is no guarantee you will get more or will not end up with less!</strong><strong>\r\n</strong></p>','Risks of Collective Bargaining','','publish','closed','closed','','risks-of-collective-bargaining-3','','','2017-01-18 06:16:07','2017-01-18 11:16:07','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=247',0,'post','',0),(248,2,'2017-01-18 06:15:48','2017-01-18 11:15:48','','ufcw-risks-of-collective-bargaining','','inherit','closed','closed','','ufcw-risks-of-collective-bargaining-2','','','2017-01-18 06:15:48','2017-01-18 11:15:48','',247,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/UFCW-Risks-of-Collective-Bargaining-1.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(249,2,'2017-01-18 06:25:10','2017-01-18 11:25:10','<h2><span style=\"color: #345a8a;\">The National Labor Relations Board has written about the Risks of Collective Bargaining:</span></h2>\r\n<strong>Are team members guaranteed the same benefits in a union contract that they had prior to collective bargaining?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>No. </strong>Your wages, benefits, work hours and employment terms may change because of bargaining. You could end up with less than you have now, more than you have now or keep the same as you have. It is not possible to know what will result from collective bargaining. In fact, the NLRB has said that:\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-242\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb1.png\" alt=\"rocb1\" width=\"792\" height=\"141\" /></a>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Does an employer have to agree to union demands?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>No</strong>. A union can only get what management is able and willing to give.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-243\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb2.png\" alt=\"rocb2\" width=\"783\" height=\"118\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Could SEIU trade away in bargaining things you enjoy now to get things it wants – like the automatic deduction of dues from your paycheck?</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-244\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/rocb3.png\" alt=\"rocb3\" width=\"777\" height=\"116\" /></a>\r\n<strong>Yes. </strong>Bargaining means give and take. At the table, some benefits may be traded for language that the union may want in a contract like dues “check off” – the automatic deduction of dues from your paycheck.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>In bargaining, everything is negotiable. There is no guarantee you will get more or will not end up with less!</strong></p>','Risks of Collective Bargaining','','publish','closed','closed','','risks-of-collective-bargaining-4','','','2017-01-18 06:37:29','2017-01-18 11:37:29','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=249',0,'post','',0),(250,2,'2017-01-18 06:24:55','2017-01-18 11:24:55','','seiu-risks-of-collective-bargaining','','inherit','closed','closed','','seiu-risks-of-collective-bargaining','','','2017-01-18 06:24:55','2017-01-18 11:24:55','',249,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/SEIU-Risks-of-Collective-Bargaining.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(251,2,'2017-01-18 06:45:49','2017-01-18 11:45:49','SEIU collected more than <strong>$153 million</strong> in dues and agency fees from members in 2015\r\n\r\nBelow is a statement from SEIU’s LM-2, a financial form that unions have to file with the U.S. Department of Labor annually.\r\n\r\nMembers pay a union for representation but in 2015, SEIU spent $22,471,500 more to pay its leaders and run the union than to represent its members.\r\n\r\nFor every $1 SEIU spent to represent members, the union spent $1.43 on its leaders and its business.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/big-business-seiu-spreadsheet.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-252\" src=\"https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/big-business-seiu-spreadsheet.png\" alt=\"big-business-seiu-spreadsheet\" width=\"885\" height=\"345\" /></a>\r\n<h3>SEIU spent:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>$52,000,946</strong> on representational activities to represent its members – including negotiating contracts and organizing new members…. That’s less than $149 per member even though members may pay as much as $900 per year in SEIU dues.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>$ 74,472,446</strong> on General Overhead, Union Administration and Benefits – salaries and benefits for union leaders and union employees</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>$10,707,506</strong> on Political Activities and Lobbying</li>\r\n</ul>','Big Business: How SEIU Spends Members’ Dues','','publish','closed','closed','','big-business-how-seiu-spends-members-dues','','','2017-01-18 06:45:49','2017-01-18 11:45:49','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=251',0,'post','',0),(252,2,'2017-01-18 06:40:47','2017-01-18 11:40:47','','big-business-seiu-spreadsheet','','inherit','closed','closed','','big-business-seiu-spreadsheet','','','2017-01-18 06:40:47','2017-01-18 11:40:47','',251,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/big-business-seiu-spreadsheet.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(253,2,'2017-01-18 06:44:52','2017-01-18 11:44:52','','seiu-financials-icon','','inherit','closed','closed','','seiu-financials-icon','','','2017-01-18 06:44:52','2017-01-18 11:44:52','',251,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/seiu-financials-icon.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(254,2,'2017-01-18 06:45:17','2017-01-18 11:45:17','','seiu-financials','','inherit','closed','closed','','seiu-financials','','','2017-01-18 06:45:17','2017-01-18 11:45:17','',251,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/SEIU-Financials.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(255,2,'2017-01-18 13:22:43','2017-01-18 18:22:43','<strong>A:</strong>    Regardless of how you vote, if a union wins the right to represent employees at BayCare, all employees in the bargaining unit will be represented by the union.  The union will expect everyone to pay dues or a representation fee.  In Florida and other right-to-work states, unions are known to use intimidation and coercion to pressure represented employees to pay dues.  Unions have been known to publicly name employees who don’t pay dues or fees on websites, bulletin boards and in union materials.','Florida is a right-to-work state.  Will I have to pay dues if the union wins the election?','','publish','closed','closed','','florida-is-a-right-to-work-state-will-i-have-to-pay-dues-if-the-union-wins-the-election','','','2017-01-18 13:22:43','2017-01-18 18:22:43','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=255',0,'post','',0),(256,2,'2017-01-18 13:23:03','2017-01-18 18:23:03','<strong>A:</strong>    Unions can make promises but they don’t have to guarantee they will accomplish those commitments.  When a union is voted in all pay and benefits are subject to negotiation, and there are no guarantees. No one, including the union representatives, knows until the contract is negotiated what the final outcome will be.','Why should I be concerned about paying money to the union?  The union says we will get improvements in pay and benefits and guaranteed hours.  Isn’t that worth the cost of dues?','','publish','closed','closed','','why-should-i-be-concerned-about-paying-money-to-the-union-the-union-says-we-will-get-improvements-in-pay-and-benefits-and-guaranteed-hours-isnt-that-worth-the-cost-of-dues','','','2017-01-18 13:23:03','2017-01-18 18:23:03','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=256',0,'post','',0),(257,2,'2017-01-18 13:23:22','2017-01-18 18:23:22','<strong>A:</strong>    You should care a lot.  If a union wins the right to represent BayCare employees, it becomes the exclusive representative for every employee whose job is part of the bargaining unit.  You will be required to follow the rules in the collective bargaining agreement – even if you don’t become a union member. This means the union will make decisions for you regarding wages, benefits and other working conditions whether you agree with them or not – an important reason for you to care.','Why should I care if my colleagues want to be in a union if I don’t have to become a union member or pay union dues?','','publish','closed','closed','','why-should-i-care-if-my-colleagues-want-to-be-in-a-union-if-i-dont-have-to-become-a-union-member-or-pay-union-dues','','','2017-01-18 13:23:22','2017-01-18 18:23:22','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=257',0,'post','',0),(258,2,'2017-01-18 13:23:41','2017-01-18 18:23:41','<strong>A:</strong>    The union does.  Dues are <strong><u>not</u></strong> determined through collective bargaining.  The hospital would have no say about the amount of dues that team members would have to pay…and you wouldn’t have much say either.','Who decides the amount of dues members pay?','','publish','closed','closed','','who-decides-the-amount-of-dues-members-pay','','','2017-01-18 13:23:41','2017-01-18 18:23:41','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=258',0,'post','',0),(259,2,'2017-01-18 13:24:06','2017-01-18 18:24:06','<strong>A:</strong>    Unions are BIG businesses.  A business needs to make money to survive.  Dues and other fees the union collects from represented employees are the primary way the union is funded.  If a union represents BayCare employees, it stands to make a lot of money from the dues and fees employees will be expected to pay.','Why would a union want to represent BayCare employees?','','publish','closed','closed','','why-would-a-union-want-to-represent-baycare-employees','','','2017-01-18 13:24:06','2017-01-18 18:24:06','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=259',0,'post','',0),(260,2,'2017-01-18 13:24:22','2017-01-18 18:24:22','<strong>A:</strong>    Dues are not an automatic 100 percent tax write-off. Union dues are deductible only if you “itemize” on your tax return.  Then, you only can deduct amounts that exceed 2% of your Adjusted Gross Income, a high threshold to meet.','Are my dues tax deductible?','','publish','closed','closed','','are-my-dues-tax-deductible','','','2017-01-18 13:24:22','2017-01-18 18:24:22','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=260',0,'post','',0),(261,2,'2017-01-18 13:24:40','2017-01-18 18:24:40','<strong>A:</strong>    Collective bargaining is a give-and-take process between management and a union to discuss wages, benefits and terms and conditions of employment. As defined by the law, collective bargaining requires an employer and the union that represents employees to:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Meet at reasonable times;</li>\r\n 	<li>Confer in good faith about wages, benefits, hours and terms and conditions of employment;</li>\r\n 	<li>Put an agreement (contract) in writing if one is reached and if it is requested.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs a result of the collective bargaining process, you could end up with less than, more than or keep the same wages and benefits that you now have. There are no guarantees despite what the union may be promising you.','What is collective bargaining?','','publish','closed','closed','','what-is-collective-bargaining','','','2017-01-18 14:50:54','2017-01-18 19:50:54','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=261',0,'post','',0),(262,2,'2017-01-18 13:24:59','2017-01-18 18:24:59','<strong>A:</strong>    Negotiation topics include wages (base pay, overtime, shift differentials), hours and any terms and conditions of employment such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>How seniority is used;</li>\r\n 	<li>How layoffs are conducted;</li>\r\n 	<li>How dues will be deducted from employees’ paychecks;</li>\r\n 	<li>How grievances (employee complaints) will be processed.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese are called “mandatory subjects of bargaining.” There also are other topics that do not have to be negotiated (“permissive subjects of bargaining”), and these include items like the hiring/firing of managers and supervisors, supplies, equipment and operational decisions.','What are some of the subjects that are bargained about during negotiations?','','publish','closed','closed','','what-are-some-of-the-subjects-that-are-bargained-about-during-negotiations','','','2017-01-18 14:50:42','2017-01-18 19:50:42','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=262',0,'post','',0),(263,2,'2017-01-18 13:25:14','2017-01-18 18:25:14','<strong>A:</strong>    Pay increases, market adjustments and benefit changes generally are frozen during negotiations. The employer must maintain what the law calls the status quo – meaning changes cannot be made without agreement with the union unless the change was planned previously or is part of a long-standing past practice.','Can an employer make changes in wages and benefits during negotiations?','','publish','closed','closed','','can-an-employer-make-changes-in-wages-and-benefits-during-negotiations','','','2017-01-18 14:50:06','2017-01-18 19:50:06','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=263',0,'post','',0),(264,2,'2017-01-18 13:25:31','2017-01-18 18:25:31','<strong>A:</strong>    Possibly. Typically, what is negotiated is a one-size-fits-all approach for work schedules that applies to all of the represented positions, regardless of unit or department preferences or practices. This may change how your work schedules currently are determined and the flexibility that you currently have.','Could employees lose schedule flexibility if the union is elected?','','publish','closed','closed','','could-employees-lose-schedule-flexibility-if-the-union-is-elected','','','2017-01-18 14:50:17','2017-01-18 19:50:17','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=264',0,'post','',0),(265,2,'2017-01-18 13:25:50','2017-01-18 18:25:50','<strong>A:</strong>    No. Once a union represents a group of employees the contract that is negotiated applies to all of the employees in a bargaining unit. The rules do not allow for an employee to “opt out” of a union contract he or she doesn’t like, nor do they allow for an employee to disregard portions of the contract that he or she doesn’t agree with.','If the union represents my group and I don’t like the contract, can I opt out?','','publish','closed','closed','','if-the-union-represents-my-group-and-i-dont-like-the-contract-can-i-opt-out','','','2017-01-18 14:50:30','2017-01-18 19:50:30','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/?p=265',0,'post','',0),(266,2,'2017-01-18 13:55:38','2017-01-18 18:55:38','<h2>Overview</h2>\nBayCare is a leading not-for-profit health care system that connects individuals and families to a wide range of services at 14 hospitals and hundreds of other convenient locations throughout the Tampa Bay and central Florida regions. Inpatient and outpatient services include acute care, primary care, imaging, laboratory, behavioral health, home care, and wellness. \n<h2>Mission</h2>\nBayCare Health System will improve the health of all we serve through community-owned health care services that set the standard for high-quality, compassionate care.\n<h2>Values</h2>\nThe values of BayCare are trust, respect, responsibility, excellence and dignity and reflect our responsibility to achieve health care excellence for our communities.\n<table class=\"TFtable\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th colspan=\"2\">BayCare by the Numbers 2016</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Year Founded</td>\n<td>1997</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Ambulatory Surgery Centers</td>\n<td>4</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Urgent Care Centers</td>\n<td>11</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Imaging Facilities</td>\n<td>13</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hospitals</td>\n<td>14</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Physicians</td>\n<td>5,400</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Beds</td>\n<td>3,491<sup>1</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td> Employees</td>\n<td> 25,600<sup>2</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Outpatient Surgeries</td>\n<td>59,761<sup>2</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Discharges</td>\n<td>158,909<sup>2</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ER Visits</td>\n<td>592,487<sup>2</span></sup>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Home Health Visits</td>\n<td>845,288<span id=\"superfix\">2</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Total Community Benefit</td>\n<td>$266.8 million<span id=\"superfix\">3</span></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<em><span id=\"superfix\">1</span> Includes beds at Morton Plant North Bay Hospital Recovery Center and St. Joseph\'s Hospital Behavioral Health Center</em>\n\n<span id=\"superfix\">2 </span>Based on 2015 information\n\n<em><span id=\"superfix\">3</span> Represents unreimbursed costs for traditional charity care, Medicaid and other means-tested programs and unbilled community services </em>\n\n<strong>BayCare Hospitals:</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/brmc\">Bartow Regional Medical Center</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/mch\">Mease Countryside Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/mdh\">Mease Dunedin Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/mph\">Morton Plant Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/mpnb\">Morton Plant North Bay Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sah\">St. Anthony\'s Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sjh\">St. Joseph\'s Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sjhn\">St. Joseph\'s Hospital-North</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sjhs\">St. Joseph\'s Hospital-South</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sjch\">St. Joseph\'s Children\'s Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sjwh\">St. Joseph\'s Women\'s Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/sfbh\">South Florida Baptist Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/whh\">Winter Haven Hospital</a>\n<a href=\"https://baycare.org/whwh\">Winter Haven Women\'s Hospital</a>\n<h3>Contact Information:</h3>\n<strong>BayCare Health System\n</strong>2985 Drew Street\nClearwater, FL 33759\n1-800-BayCare (1-800-229-2273)','About','','inherit','closed','closed','','32-autosave-v1','','','2017-01-18 13:55:38','2017-01-18 18:55:38','',32,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/32-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(267,2,'2017-01-18 14:42:31','2017-01-18 19:42:31','<div class=\"row\">\n<div class=\"col grid_12_of_12\">\n<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Welcome to the BayCare Know the Facts Website</h1>\nWe developed this website to help employees learn about their legal rights regarding unions, the facts about union’s and about BayCare’s preference to continue working directly, flexibly with employees. We encourage you to check this site regularly for factual, important and up-to-date information that will help you decide whether or not union representation if right for you and your family.\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"row\">\n<div class=\"col grid_3_of_12\">\n</div>\n<div class=\"col grid_6_of_12\">\n<h2>BayCare\'s Philosophy About Unions</h2>\n<script src=\"//fast.wistia.com/embed/medias/mxgp2f8vts.jsonp\" async></script><script src=\"//fast.wistia.com/assets/external/E-v1.js\" async></script>\n<div class=\"wistia_responsive_padding\" style=\"padding: 56.25% 0 0 0; position: relative;\">\n<div class=\"wistia_responsive_wrapper\" style=\"height: 100%; left: 0; position: absolute; top: 0; width: 100%;\">\n<div class=\"wistia_embed wistia_async_mxgp2f8vts videoFoam=true\" style=\"height: 100%; width: 100%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"col grid_3_of_12\">\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"row\">\n<div class=\"col grid_12_of_12\">\n<div class=\"nn-ds-frm\">\n<h2>Calculate your union dues and compare it to saving for retirement</h2>\n[gravityform id=\"3\" title=\"false\" description=\"false\"]\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>','Home','','inherit','closed','closed','','31-autosave-v1','','','2017-01-18 14:42:31','2017-01-18 19:42:31','',31,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/31-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(268,2,'2017-01-18 14:49:26','2017-01-18 19:49:26','<strong>A:</strong>    No. Once a union represents a group of employees the contract that is negotiated applies to all of the employees in a bargaining unit. The rules do not allow for an employee to “opt out” of a union contract he or she doesn’t like, nor do they allow for an employee to disregard portions of the contract that he or she doesn’t agree with.','If the union represents my group and I don’t like the contract, can I opt out?','','publish','closed','closed','','if-the-union-represents-my-group-and-i-dont-like-the-contract-can-i-opt-out-2','','','2017-01-18 14:52:15','2017-01-18 19:52:15','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/if-the-union-represents-my-group-and-i-dont-like-the-contract-can-i-opt-out-2/',0,'post','',0),(269,2,'2017-01-18 14:49:28','2017-01-18 19:49:28','<strong>A:</strong>    Possibly. Typically, what is negotiated is a one-size-fits-all approach for work schedules that applies to all of the represented positions, regardless of unit or department preferences or practices. This may change how your work schedules currently are determined and the flexibility that you currently have.','Could employees lose schedule flexibility if the union is elected?','','publish','closed','closed','','could-employees-lose-schedule-flexibility-if-the-union-is-elected-2','','','2017-01-18 14:52:05','2017-01-18 19:52:05','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/could-employees-lose-schedule-flexibility-if-the-union-is-elected-2/',0,'post','',0),(270,2,'2017-01-18 14:49:31','2017-01-18 19:49:31','<strong>A:</strong>    Pay increases, market adjustments and benefit changes generally are frozen during negotiations. The employer must maintain what the law calls the status quo – meaning changes cannot be made without agreement with the union unless the change was planned previously or is part of a long-standing past practice.','Can an employer make changes in wages and benefits during negotiations?','','publish','closed','closed','','can-an-employer-make-changes-in-wages-and-benefits-during-negotiations-2','','','2017-01-18 14:51:53','2017-01-18 19:51:53','',0,'https://baycareknowthefacts.org/can-an-employer-make-changes-in-wages-and-benefits-during-negotiations-2/',0